[h1]Variable City Nightwatch Demo Preview: Five Chapters, Builds, and the Road Ahead[/h1]

[b]This pre-demo announcement sets expectations for the playable scope, the feedback we are looking for, and the Steam release work still ahead.[/b]

Hello, night-shift debuggers. Variable City Nightwatch is moving from a web-playable build toward a Steam Demo. The current pipeline now connects five playable chapters, chapter practice, build choices, boss phases, pause and settings, local saves, achievement drafts, store assets, and a desktop shell.

[h2]What the Demo Is Built to Show[/h2]
The demo path focuses on five compact nightwatch chapters. The office, metro platform, hash market, promise tower, and whitebox core each use different map props, hazards, interaction points, and enemy mixes instead of simple palette swaps.

[h2]Builds and Boss Readability[/h2]
Weapons, variable blessings, concept resonance, and in-run upgrades are meant to create visible build differences. Bosses use phases, attack rhythms, and weak windows so fights can be read, dodged, and countered through player choices.

[h2]What Feedback Helps Most[/h2]
The most useful feedback right now is whether maps are readable, enemy mechanics feel strange but fair, and build choices change how a run plays. Reports about blocked progression, missing pickups, controls, audio balance, or unclear visual warnings are also especially helpful.

[h2]Roadmap[/h2]
[list]
[*] Resolve the Electron binary install blocker and pass the automated desktop smoke test.
[*] Stress-test the five-chapter route, save recovery, performance, and missing asset checks.
[*] Add Steam Input, Steam achievements, Steam Cloud validation, and a first gameplay trailer.
[/list]

[h2]Feedback Channels[/h2]
[list]
[*] Steam community discussions for version feedback and player questions.
[*] The GitHub Pages web build for checking whether the browser demo remains playable.
[*] The future Steam Demo page for desktop compatibility feedback.
[/list]

Thank you for walking the night shift with us. Each update should be verifiable, replayable, and visible in the actual game.

